public class JsHTMLElement
extends DOM2HTML.HTMLElement.Prototype

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.HTMLElement class.

Each tag in an HTML document is represented by a JsHTMLElement object. This class defines properties that represent the attributes shared by all HTML elements.

following HTML tags do not have any properties other than those defined and fully described by JsHTMLElement: <abbr>, <acronym>, <address>, <b>, <bdo>, <big>, <center>, <cite>, <code>, <dd>, <dfn>, <dt>, <em>, <i>, <kbd>, <noframes>, <noscript>, <s>, <samp>, <small>, <span>, <strike>, <strong>, <sub>, <sup>, <tt>, <u>, <var>.

Most HTML tags define properties other than those explicitly defined in this class. The DOM Level 2 HTML specification defines tag-specific interfaces for these tags, so that all standard HTML attributes have a corresponding standard JavaScript property. Typically, a tag named Tag has a tag-specific opaque class named JsHTMLTagElement. In a few cases, two or more related tags share a single class, as in the case of the <h1> through <h6> tags, which are all represented by the JsHTMLHeadingElement class.

Most of these tag-specific classes do nothing more than define a JavaScript property for each attribute of the HTML tag. The JavaScript properties have the same names as the attributes and use lower-case or, when the attribute name consists of multiple words, mixed case. When an HTML attribute name is a reserved word in Java or JavaScript, the property name is changed slightly.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

className

public static final Value.String.Member className

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers to the value of the class attribute of the element, which specifies zero or more space-separated CSS class names. Note that this property is not named "class" because that name is a reserved word in Java and JavaScript.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this static field to the identifier of the field name.

innerHTML

public static final Value.String.Member innerHTML

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers to a read/write string that specifies the HTML text that is contained within the element, not including the opening and closing tags of the element itself. Querying this property returns the content of the element as a string of HTML text. Setting this property to a string of HTML text replaces the content of the element with the parsed representation of the HTML. You cannot set this property while the document is loading (see JsHTMLDocument.write(String) for this ability). This is a nonstandard property that originated in IE 4. It has been implemented by all modern browsers.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this static field to the identifier of the field name.

scrollHeight

public static final Value.Number.Member scrollHeight

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers to the overall height, in pixels, of an element. When an element has scrollbars (because of the CSS overflow attribute, for example) the property differs from offsetHeight, which simply reports the height of the visible portion of the element. This is non-standard but well-supported property.

scrollLeft

public static final Value.Number.Member scrollLeft

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers to the number of pixels that have scrolled off the left edge of the element. The property is useful only for elements with scrollbars, such as elements with the CSS overflow attribute set to auto. This property is also defined on the <body> or <html> tag of the document (this is browser-dependent) and specifies the amount of scrolling for the document as a whole. Note that this property does not specify the amount of scrolling in an <iframe> tag. This is a non-standard but well-supported property.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this static field to the identifier of the field name.

offsetParent

public static final JsHTMLElement.Member offsetParent

An opaque static field defining a member that is named by the field name without a qualifying member and to access the property of the name on an object.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object refers a node object specifying the container element that defines the coordinate system in which offsetLeft and offsetTop are measured. For most elements, offsetParent is the JsHTMLDocument object that contains them. However, if an element has a dynamically positioned container, the dynamically positioned element is the offsetParent. In some browsers, table cells are positioned relative to the row in which they are contained, rather than relative to the containing document. This is a nonstandard but well-supported property.

Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this static field to the identifier of the field name.

The property, identified by this member, of a JsHTMLElement object is a reference to an event handler function invoked when the user releases a mouse button.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsElement.addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsElement.attachEvent(String, JsFunction)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must resolve the member of this static field to the identifier of the field name.

scrollIntoView

public final void scrollIntoView()

Scrolls the document so the element is visible at the top or bottom of the window.

If an HTML element is not currently visible in the window, this method scrolls the document so that it becomes visible. For elements that accept the keyboard focus, such as the JsHTMLInputElement elements, the JsHTMLInputElement.focus() method implicitly performs this same scroll-into-view operation.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
scrollIntoView(Boolean), scrollIntoView(JsBoolean), scrollIntoView(Value)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

scrollIntoView

public final void scrollIntoView(java.lang.Boolean top)

Scrolls the document so the element is visible at the top or bottom of the window.

If an HTML element is not currently visible in the window, this method scrolls the document so that it becomes visible. For elements that accept the keyboard focus, such as the JsHTMLInputElement elements, the JsHTMLInputElement.focus() method implicitly performs this same scroll-into-view operation. The top argument is an optional hint about whether the element should be scrolled to the top or bottom of the window.

Parameters:
top - An optional boolean argument specifying whether the element should be scrolled to the top (true) or bottom (false) of the screen. This argument is not supported by all browsers, and elements near the top or bottom of a document cannot usually be scrolled to the opposite edge of the window, so this argument should be considered only a hint.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
scrollIntoView(), scrollIntoView(JsBoolean), scrollIntoView(Value)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.
